      <p>Over the past two years, we have concentrated our efforts on a low-cost, high-impact intervention: supplying Kangaroo Mother Care (KMC) carriers to the Institute of Neonatology in Kyiv. This simple, evidence-based method is saving newborn lives every day, particularly in a health system strained by conflict and infrastructure disruption.</p>

      <h2>Kangaroo Mother Care in Ukraine</h2>
      <p>From the beginning of the war the Fellowship has mobilised significant medical aid to Ukraine. After 18 months of emergency medical aid, we made a strategic decision to support maternity care &ndash; focusing mainly on babies born with a low birth weight. We concluded that the most effective way to give newborn babies the best chance of survival is Kangaroo Mother Care (KMC).</p>
      <p>KMC involves keeping small (preterm) babies skin-to-skin with their mother (or another family member), with exclusive breast or breast-milk feeding and medical assessment. Studies of KMC report increased survival, decreased infection, improved nutrition and growth and possible improved development. Its benefits extend far beyond the well-known advantages of skin-to-skin care, and the support it has provided to perinatal facilities in Ukraine has exceeded all expectations.</p>
      <p>In Ukraine, babies are born into a terrifying world of war. Newborn babies are spending the first days of their lives in shelters and basements (UNICEF). KMC is a simple, life-saving tool.</p>

      <h3>A vital device for mums in areas of conflict</h3>
      <p>During active hostilities, the number of premature births increases, and the lack of electricity complicates the uninterrupted operation of equipment in neonatal wards. Because of unpredictable bombings, mothers must run to bomb shelters in haste. With the help of Kangaroo carriers, we can increase the safety of both mothers and babies, even in these extreme circumstances.</p>
      <p>In addition to the carriers themselves, a large part of the project is dedicated to training healthcare professionals &ndash; as well as parents of premature babies &ndash; how to implement Kangaroo Mother Care effectively, to ensure the most effective and efficient care.</p>
      <p>The carriers are manufactured in Moldova by Ascend Group SRL (Director Geta Rasciuc &ndash; a sling and carrier expert with over 17 years of experience and a board member of the International Council of Babywearing Consulting Schools), using local materials. They are made in accordance with the EU safety standard EN 13209-1, using materials that meet the clinical hygiene requirements for washing at high temperatures.</p>
      <p>The Fellowship has supplied 8,000 KMC carriers to neonatal units in Ukraine and has received excellent feedback from medical and nursing staff as well as mums and dads.</p>
      <img src="/images/2024/07/IMG-20240123-WA0017.jpg" alt="Mother holding her premature baby skin-to-skin in a Kangaroo Mother Care carrier">

      <h3>Voices from Ukraine</h3>
      <blockquote>
        <p>&ldquo;Children make up 24% of the population &mdash; but they are one hundred percent of our future. By investing in the survival of premature babies, by improving the care of all newborns, and by ensuring that mothers can reach bomb shelters quickly and safely, we are directly shaping what tomorrow will look like for a country at war.</p>
        <p>Parents live with an elevated level of stress, which affects their wellbeing and that of their children. When mothers carry their infants in baby wraps their oxytocin levels rise &mdash; reducing stress and strengthening emotional connection. This helps them cope with daily challenges, and over time it becomes profoundly important for infants, who are nurtured by calmer, less stressed mothers.</p>
        <p>Every child matters &mdash; especially in a country facing war and the demographic consequences of war. Baby carriers have been shown to be easy to use, safe, and to provide stability for the baby as the mother moves around. Many thanks to the Rotary Fellowship for this.&rdquo;</p>
        <p>&mdash; <cite>Olga Nicolyuk, Ukraine</cite></p>
      </blockquote>
      <blockquote>
        <p>&ldquo;I will say now, as a parent, that it&rsquo;s really important for a mum to be close to her children and free to move around. I spent January and February in Okhmatdyt hospital in Kyiv with my elder child. In those months there was a lot of bombing, a lot of attacks, so I had to take my elder child and my little daughter to the shelter many times. I know how important these carriers are. Thank you.&rdquo;</p>
        <p>&mdash; <cite>Alyona Kovriga, Ukraine</cite></p>
      </blockquote>

